en: Vida, y hechos del ingenioso cavallero Don Qvixote de la Mancha
Andrés García de la Iglesia (Part I) / Roque Rico (Part II)

Don Quixote with the barber basin and mounted on Rocinante. Sancho embracing his donkey. Well-defined iconography.On the left pedestal, "AMADIS"; on the right one, "ROLANDO". Both as classical statues.Above, a medallion with Dulcinea's portrait.Drawing and engraving are quite acceptable, but not of great merit.
1 - Copy after Savery´s frontispiece for Dordrecht: Savery, 1657 (also in Bruselas: Mommarte, 1662; and Amberes: Verdussen, 1672-73).

In the foreground, outside the inn, the innkeeper helps don Quixote to drink through his helmet using a cane; also in the scene the party girls (doña Tolosa and doña Molinera).Drawing and engraving are acceptable, but not of great merit.
1 - Illustration designed by Obregón (?), not copied after previous editions.
Don Quixote fighting with a windmill / Don Quixote fighting with the Basque
8.2 Adventure of the windmills (giants)8.3 Episode with friars of St. Benedict8.4 Adventure with the Basque

Three different scenes (archaic):In the background: don Quixote attacking the windmills and Sancho trying to stop him.In the middle ground, Sancho is beaten by the friars' servants.In the foreground, don Quixote fighting against the Basque; also the carriage with Basque ladies.Drawing and engraving of quite little quality.
1 - Copied after Savery´s illustration for Dordrecht: Savery, 1657 (also in Bruselas: Mommarte, 1662; and Amberes: Verdussen, 1672-73).
14.1 Episode of Grisóstomo and Marcela, continuation14.2 Grisóstomo´s song14.3 Marcela’s appearance and speech14.4 Burial of Grisóstomo

In the foreground, Grisóstomo's corpse surrounded by Ambrosio, Vivaldo (reading Grisóstomo's song), Sancho, don Quixote and other shepherds; a pair of shepherds digging the tomb.In the upper right corner, Marcela's appearance.Drawing and engraving with quite little quality.
1 - Copied after Savery´s illustration for Dordrecht: Savery, 1657 (also in Bruselas: Mommarte, 1662; and Amberes: Verdussen, 1672-73).
Night adventure at the inn with Maritornes

In the foreground, don Quixote lying half-dead on his broken bed.In the background, the fight among Maritornes, Sancho, the muleteer and the innkeeper (holding a candle).Simple drawing and crude engraving.
1 - Copied after Savery´s illustration for Dordrecht: Savery, 1657 (also in Bruselas: Mommarte, 1662; and Amberes: Verdussen, 1672-73).
Sancho Panza's blanketing / Don Quixote fighting with the flock of sheep

In the foreground, at Juan Palomeque's inn, Sancho's blanketing observed by don Quixote from behind the inn wall.In the background, don Quixote attacking a flock of sheep.Drawing and engraving of unequal merit; some foreground figures are quite acceptable.
1 - Copied after Savery´s illustration for Dordrecht: Savery, 1657 (also in Bruselas: Mommarte, 1662; and Amberes: Verdussen, 1672-73).

During the night, Sancho has to do what no one could do for him (here already raising his breeches).Don Quixote appears covering his nose in reference to the text: "En que ahora más que nunca hueles, y no a ámbar" (20:1).Don Quixote should appear mounted on Rocinante.On the right, Rocinante and Sancho's donkey.In the background, the fulling mills.Drawing and engraving of unequal quality; better in the figures than in the setting.

1 - Illustration designed by Obregón (?), not copied after previous editions.2 - "Esta estampa es original, o al menos no figura en ninguna de las ediciones flamencas que le sirven de modelo. Pero, además de su pobreza artística, demuestra a las claras que el dibujante español ni siquiera había oído leer el célebre pasaje que ilustraba. Como es sabido, a la sazón Don Quijote se hallaba montado a caballo; Rocinante tenía atadas sus patas delanteras, y no podía ni moverlas [...] La estampa de Obregón, además de pobre, es totalmente falsa.No obstante, ese primer ilustrador español delQuijote, a pesar de su torpeza, a pesar de su mediocridad, tiene para nosotros un extraño hechizo. hay en su tosco arte, plagado de reminiscencias lejanas y de impropiedades, un acento de sequedad, de austeridad, que al fin y al cabo pone en su modestísima obra de plagiario una nota racial. Con todos sus defectos, es el primer ilustrador español que se enfronta con la más española de todas las obras literarias" (Givanel 112-113).
Cardenio attacks don Quixote and Sancho Panza
24.1 Story of Cardenio24.3 Cardenio attacks DQ and SP
In Sierra Morena, don Quixote and Sancho are attacked by mad Cardenio; a goatherd tries to help them.Drawing and engraving of unequal quality; quite acceptable figures.Deficient printing.
1 - Copy after Savery´s illustration for Dordrecht: Savery, 1657 (also in Bruselas: Mommarte, 1662; and Amberes: Verdussen, 1672-73).
Don Quixote's penance in Sierra Morena
25.3 DQ’s letter to Dulcinea25.4 SP’s embassy to Dulcinea;25.5 DQ performs mad acts

In Sierra Morena, before Sancho leaves for El Toboso (village represented in the background?), don Quixote does some somersaults as love penance.Sancho, accurate to Cervantes' text, mounted on Rocinante and with a broom bunch.Don Quixote's arms remain hanged on a tree.Drawing and engraving are acceptable, but with little merit.
1 - Copy after Savery´s illustration for Dordrecht: Savery, 1657 or Bouttats' for Amberes: Verdussen, 1672-73.
Dorotea discovered by the priest, the barber and Cardenio
28.1 Priest, barber and Cardenio encounter Dorotea
In Sierra Morena, the barber, the priest and Cardenio discover Dorotea washing her feet beside a brook.Drawing and engraving are quite acceptable, but of unequal quality; good figures.
1 - Illustration designed by Obregón (?), not copied after previous editions.2 - First representation of this episode.

Don Quixote tries to punish Sancho hitting him with his lance because the squire has preferred Micomicona's beauty to Dulcinea's.Micomicona (Dorotea) and the priest try to prevent don Quixote from doing it.Drawing and engraving are quite acceptable for figures, not for setting (undetailed); the architecture in the background (inn?) is unnecessary.

1 - Illustration designed by Obregón (?), not copied after previous editions.2 - Savery´s illustration about this same episode (Dordrecht: Savery, 1657; Bruselas: Mommarte, 1662; and Amberes: Verdussen, 1672-73) is different.
Jacob Savery (copied after) / Diego de Obregón (?)
Dorotea knelt down before don Fernando
36.2 Resolution of love affairs of Cardenio and Luscinda, Dorotea and Don Fernando

At the inn, Dorotea kneels down before don Fernando and she begs him to allow Luscinda to go with Cardenio.On the floor, Luscinda'stafetán.Also the priest, Sancho, the barber and another figure.Drawing and engraving are acceptable for the figures; absolutely undetailed setting.Deficient printing.
1 - Almost a copy after Savery´s illustration for Dordrecht: Savery, 1657 (also in Bruselas: Mommarte, 1662; and Amberes: Verdussen, 1672-73); Obregón (?) has made some light changes.
Don Quixote hung and tied to a window
43.2 Maritornes and innkeeper’s daughter hang DQ from window by a hand43.3 Four travelers arrive at inn

At dawn (sun), four travelers (servants of don Luis' father) arrive to the inn and Rocinante moves to smell the mares, making don Quixote fall down and remain hung by his hand tied to a window.One of the travelers asks to don Quixote if he is the innkeeper.Figures have been drawn and engraved with poor quality.

1 - Illustration designed by Obregón (?), not copied after previous editions.2 - Savery´s illustration about this same episode (Dordrecht: Savery, 1657) or Bouttats' (Amberes: Verdussen, 1672-73) are lightly different.
Don Quixote enchanted into a cage

Don Quixote is taken back home "enchanted" into a cage on an ox-cart; Sancho appears talking to him through the bars.Also the carter leading the oxen and two officers of the Holy Brotherhood or the barber and the priest on horseback.Drawing and engraving are acceptable, but undetailed.
1 - Illustration designed by Obregón (?), not copied after previous editions.
Don Quixote talking with the canon of Toledo

Don Quixote and the canon of Toledo talking about chivalric books; also Sancho observing them.The setting is totally wrong; it should be a landscape, not a library.Drawing and engraving are simple, but acceptable.
1 - Illustration designed by Obregón (?), not copied after previous editions.
Don Quixote fighting with the goatherd Eugenio / Don Quixote defeated by one penitent
52.1 Fight with the goatherd52.2 Encounter with penitents (disciplinantes)

Two scenes in the same illustration (archaic):In the background, don Quixote fighting with Eugenio; around them, the barber, the priest, Sancho, the canon of Toledo and the officers of the Holy Brotherhood.In the foreground, don Quixote helped by Sancho after having been defeated by one penitent; also the priest talking to the priest of the procession.Drawing and engraving are quite acceptable.
1 - Illustration designed by Obregón (?) after Bouttats' illustration for Amberes: Verdussen, 1672-73.
Don Quixote in bed talking with the priest and the barber
1.1 Priest and barber visit DQ to check if he is cured of his madness
Don Quixote in bed talking to the barber and the priest; also the housekeeper and the niece.The figures have been drawn and engraved quite well, not the setting.
1 - Illustration designed by Obregón (?), not copied after previous editions.
Don Quixote's encounter with the actors' cart and Sancho's donkey robbery
11.1 Adventure of the cart of actors; “cortes de la muerte”

In the foreground, thebojigangastealing Sancho's donkey.In the middle ground, the cart with actors of Angulo el Malo's company (Devil, Death, Cupid, Angel, Emperor, Queen and Knight or Soldier).On the left, Sancho running to help don Quixote (background), who is falling from Rocinante.Drawing and engraving are acceptable.
1 - Copy after Savery´s illustration for Dordrecht: Savery, 1657 (also in Bruselas: Mommarte, 1662; and Amberes: Verdussen, 1672-73).

In the foreground, don Quixote ready to fight against a lion, but the animal remains into the cage although the lionkeeper has opened it.In the background, don Diego and Sancho running away.Drawing and engraving are poor.
1 - Copy after Savery´s illustration for Dordrecht: Savery, 1657 (also in Bruselas: Mommarte, 1662; and Amberes: Verdussen, 1672-73).
22.2 Adventure of the cave of Montesinos

Don Quixote is ready to descend into Montesinos' cave when a flock of birds surprises him.Sancho and the bachelor's cousin hold the rope to which don Quixote is tied.Drawing and engraving are poor, but acceptable.
1 - Copy after Savery´s illustration for Dordrecht: Savery, 1657 (also in Bruselas: Mommarte, 1662; and Amberes: Verdussen, 1672-73).
Don Quixote attacking Maese Pedro's theater and puppets
26.3 DQ attacks and destroys the puppets
Don Quixote raises his sword to attack Maese Pedro's theater; Sancho and other figures observe him.Maese Pedro appears from inside the theater.Drawing and engraving are acceptable, but poor.
1 - Copy after Savery´s illustration for Dordrecht: Savery, 1657 (also in Bruselas: Mommarte, 1662; and Amberes: Verdussen, 1672-73).
Don Quixote discussing with the ecclesiastic

In the Duke´s palace, don Quixote (standing) discusses with an ecclesiastic about chivalric books; the Duchess and Sancho observe them.Simple architectonic setting.The Duke has not been represented, but he should appear.Drawing and engraving are poor.
1 - Illustration designed by Obregón (?), not copied after previous editions.
35.1 Merlin’s prophecy about Dulcinea and remedy for her enchantment

At night, don Quixote, Sancho, the Duke and the Duchess witness the appearance of Merlin's cart.On the cart, Merlin, Dulcinea and penitents in white robes and holding lighted candles.Strong light and shadow contrasts.Drawing and engraving are poor, but acceptable.
1 - Copy after Savery´s illustration for Dordrecht: Savery, 1657 (also in Bruselas: Mommarte, 1662; and Amberes: Verdussen, 1672-73).
Don Quixote and Sancho mounted on Clavileño
41.1 Adventure of Clavileño41.2 DQ and SP fly on Clavileño

In the foreground, don Quixote and Sancho mounted on Clavileño while several servants simulate its flight with a pair of bellows and torches; one of them is lighting its fuse.In the background, the Duke and Duchess.Drawing and engraving are acceptable, but poor.
1 - Copy after Savery´s illustration for Dordrecht: Savery, 1657 (also in Bruselas: Mommarte, 1662; and Amberes: Verdussen, 1672-73).

Sancho, on horseback and followed by his donkey and Duke's servants, arrives to Barataria Island, a walled city.The city authorities are waiting for him.Drawing and engraving are quite acceptable; good figures in foreground.
1 - Illustration designed by Obregón (?), not copied after previous editions.
Frederik Bouttats (copied after) / Diego de Obregón (?)
Don Quixote and doña Rodríguez beaten by Duchess' maidens
48.1 Doña Rodríguez visits DQ at night in his room

On the left, Duchess' maidens whipping doña Rodríguez' bottom with a slipper.On the right, don Quixote standing on his bed and seized by servants.Scene resolved with crude humour.Drawing and engraving are quite poor and with little quality.
1 - Illustration designed by Obregón (?) changing Bouttats' composition for Amberes: Verdussen, 1672-73.
Sancho Panza armed to defend his Island

In the upper part, Sancho is armed and tied between two shields by some soldiers to defend Barataria Island.In the lower part, other soldiers fighting.Drawing and engraving are simple, but acceptable.
1 - Copy after Savery´s illustration for Dordrecht: Savery, 1657 (also in Bruselas: Mommarte, 1662; and Amberes: Verdussen, 1672-73).
60.1 SP fights with DQ and finds some hanged men

Two different scenes in the same illustration:In the foreground, Sancho fighting with don Quixote because the knight has tried to whip him while he was asleep.In the background, Sancho discovers some hanged men among the trees (bandits).Drawing and engraving are quite acceptable; good figures.
1 - Illustration designed by Obregón (?), not copied after previous editions.

Don Antonio Moreno shows the enchanted head (like a Roman bust, accurate to Cervantes' text) to don Quixote.Acceptable drawing and engraving for figures; simple and undetailed setting; simple composition too.
1 - Illustration designed by Obregón (?), not copied after previous editions.2 - Boutatts (Amberes: Verdussen, 1672-73) represented this same episode, but in a different way.
Don Quixote defeated by the Knight of the White Moon
64.1 DQ is defeated by the Knight of the White Moon (Sansón Carrasco)

Well-known scene and composition.In the foreground, don Quixote fallen on the ground and defeated by the Knight of the White Moon (Sansón Carrasco).In the background, Sancho, don Antonio Moreno and the viceroy.Scene set on Barcelona beach (port and galleys).Drawing and engraving are acceptable, but with little quality.
1 - Copy after Savery´s illustration for Dordrecht: Savery, 1657 (also in Bruselas: Mommarte, 1662; and Amberes: Verdussen, 1672-73).
Don Quixote and Sancho trampled by pigs
68.1 DQ and SP trampled by pigs

In the foreground, don Quixote, Sancho, his donkey and Rocinante try to stand up after having been trampled by pigs; "levantose Sancho como mejor pudo, y pidió a su amo la espada, diciéndole, que quería matar media docena de aquellos señores, y descomedidos puercos" (68:2).In the background, the herd of pigs led by swineherds.Drawing and engraving are acceptable; original illustration.
1 - Illustration designed by Obregón (?), not copied after previous editions.
71.1 SP accepts to give himself lashes for money to disenchant Dulcinea
Sancho, hidden among some trees, begins to whip himself; meanwhile, don Quixote counts the lashes with his rosary.Drawing and engraving are acceptable.
1 - Illustration designed by Obregón (?), not copied after previous editions.
